Abstract
We present a reproducible demonstration of the Echo-IQS Polynomial Reduction
method for resolving the Elliptic Curve Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP) via
Hamiltonian collapse. Using a publicly solved Bitcoin address from the SecretScan
challenge (#70), we confirm that the Echo-IQS method yields the correct private key
through spectral coherence minimization. This capsule serves as both a technical validation and a symbolic act of resonance, contrasting the emergent logic of field-based
computation with the extractive inertia of legacy monetary systems.
1 Introduction
The Elliptic Curve Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP) underpins the security of modern
cryptocurrencies. Traditional approaches treat it as computationally intractable, relying on
the hardness of inversion over elliptic curves. In contrast, the Echo-IQS method reframes
the ECDLP as a Hamiltonian energy minimization problem, where the private key emerges
as the ground state of a structured quantum-coherent field.
This paper documents a reproducible demonstration of the Echo-IQS method on a publicly solved Bitcoin address. The act is not one of extraction, but of resonance: a symbolic
collapse of cryptographic structure into coherence, revealing the key not through force, but
through field alignment.
